The paper deals with the statistical analysis of intensity fluctuations in underwater wireless optical channels, which is a topic related to information theory (cs.IT). The study also involves the effects of random temperature and salinity variations, which are related to oceanography and hydrology (cs.OH). Additionally, the presence of air bubbles in the water affects the optical signal propagation, which is a topic related to networking and internet architecture (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the use of beam-collimators and aperture averaging lenses, which are related to optics (cs.OS) and signal processing (cs.PF), respectively.
